[2022-07-27 10:12:52,660] INFO::searchPhraseQuery() Search for 5 For Brahman ( Priesthood) he bindsa Brahman to the stake ; for Kshatra ( Royalty ) aRaj-nya; for the Maruts @ Vaisya ; for Penance a Sidra ; for Darkness a robber ; for Hell a homicide or a man who hai lost his consecrated fire; for Misfortune a eunuch; for Venality an Ayogd ; for Kama a harlot ; for Excessive Noise a Magadha ; ‘Books XXX, and XXXI. treat of the Purushanedha or Human Sacrifice, an old-established custom among almost all natins of antiquity. The cere- mony was to be performed by » Brahman or a ajanya, and was expected to obtain for the Sacrificer universal preéminenee and every blessing which the Horse-sacrifice might have failed to secure, The ritual resembles in many respects that of the Agvamedha; man, tie noblest victim, being ac- tually or symbolicaily sacrificed instead of the Horse, and men and women of various tribes, figures, complexions, characters, and professions being at- tached to the sacrificial stakes in place of th» tame and wild animals enu- merated in Book XXIV. These nominal victims were afterwards released uninjured, and, so far asthe text of the Whice Yajurveda goes, the whole ceremony was Inerely emblematical, » type of the allegorical self-immola- tion of Purusha, Embodied Spirit or the Cosmic Man. See Colebrooke, Miscellaneous Essays, II.; Weber, IndischeStreifen, I. 54 seq. ; Wilson, Selected Works, II. 247 seq ; Muir, Origiral Sanskrit Texts, IV. 289, note ; Oldenberg, Religion des Veda, p. 865; Romesh Chunder Dutt, Civilization in Ancient India, I. 274, 275 (first edition); Max Miller, Ancient Sanskrit Literature, 419 seq. ; Vedic India (Story cf the Nations Series), pp. 406— 413; A, Hillebrandt, Ritual-Litteratur, p. 153. perhaps ‘a gambler,’ or ‘an uuchaste woman,’ as Prof. Weber translates in Indische Streifen, I. 76, where, and in the following pages, Prof. W. has given a version, with explanatory notes, of the whole list of victims and objects to which t