[2022-07-27 10:12:54,821] INFO::searchPhraseQuery() Search for 10 The object of the Pravargya, which is a purificatory and introductory + ceremony like Diksha or Consecration (IV. 2; V. 6) is the bodily regeut ration of the Sacrificer, the provision of a heavenly body with which alos he is permitted to enter the residence of the Gods (Haug, Ait Brik manam, IL 42, note). At the conclusion of the ceremony, therefore, the ! sacrificial materials are so arranged as to form the semblance of a hua figure. The Mahaviras represent the head ; the Prastara or sacrificial but of gras the hair ; the two milk-veszels are his eara ; the plates of gold and silver his eyes ; the Raubipacake potsherds represent the heels ; the cot tents of the caldron are the blood, and so on (see Hillebrandt, Ritual-Lit teratur, p.185), The formulas contained in this verve provide the Pravargyt man with the bodily parts enymerated, and the regeneration of the Secrif cer is thus completed, Faculties and feelings are imparted by the formals which follow. VERSE 13.) W4ITE YAJURVEDA. 308 yielded 0 results in 0.0011951923370361328 seconds.
